Museums

AMERICAN MUSEUM OF NATURAL HISTORY, Central Park West and 79th Street. Through Aug. 7, "Exploring Bolivia's Biodiversity," an exhibition of more than 30 color photographs. Through May 30, "The Butterfly Conservatory: Tropical Butterflies Alive in Winter," a walk-in display of hundreds of live specimens. Through the spring, "Vital Variety: A Visual Celebration of Invertebrate Biodiversity," an exhibition of 24 large-format color photographs by the entomologist Piotr Naskrecki, in the gallery next to the Imax theater. Through July, "Totems to Turquoise: Native North American Jewelry Arts of the Northwest," with more than 500 pieces of contemporary and historic jewelry. The Arthur Ross Hall of Meteorites displays the 34-ton Ahnighito meteorite, the world's largest. In the Imax theater, "Vikings: Journey to New Worlds," and "Jane Goodall's Wild Chimpanzees." Tickets to one Imax feature, including museum admission, are $19; students and 60+, $14; children under 12, $11. Timed tickets to the "Butterfly Conservatory" and general admission to "Totems to Turquoise" are $19; students and 60+ and for those 12 and younger, $14. Suggested general admission: $13; students and 60+, $10; 12 and younger, $7.50; under 2, free. Combination tickets are available, including museum and Rose Center admission and the Hayden Planetarium space show: $22; students and 60+, $16.50; 12 and younger, $13; under 2, free. Museum hours: daily, 10 a.m. to 5:45 p.m., except the first Friday of most months, when the Rose Center is open until 8:45 p.m. for "Starry Nights"; tonight at 6 and 7:30, the Lynne Arriale Trio. Information: amnh.org; (212)769-5100 or (212)769-5200.

MUSEUM OF THE CITY OF NEW YORK, Fifth Avenue at 103rd Street. The museum collects, preserves and presents material related to the city's history. Tomorrow at 3 p.m., "Nuyorican Cinema: Films of the Puerto Rican Diaspora," a guided presentation of film clips about Puerto Ricans born or raised in New York; free with museum admission. Through July 7, "Glamour, New York Style" examines the influence of New York's fashion trend setters with exhibits including 50 couture gowns; Sunday at 11 a.m. and 2 p.m., a discussion and tour of the exhibit. Reservations required. Fee: $30, $25 for students, members and 62+. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Suggested admission: $7; 62+, students and children, $5; families, $15. Information: (212)534-1672.

MUSEUM OF THE MOVING IMAGE, 36-01 35th Avenue, at 36th Street, Astoria, Queens. Running through May 30, "Digital Play: Reloaded," an interactive display of video and digital games including Pac-Mondrian, Pac Man, Donkey Kong and Stepmania. Tomorrow through April 10, "Marx Brothers Classics." This weekend: "Animal Crackers," (1930), directed by Victor Heerman (tomorrow at 2 p.m.); "A Night at the Opera," (1932), directed by Sam Wood (tomorrow at 4 p.m. and Sunday at 2 p.m.); "A Day at the Races," (1937), directed by Wood (Sunday at 4 p.m.). Also showing this weekend: "Joint Security Area," (2000), directed by Park Chan-Wook (tonight at 7:30); and "The Blue Angel," (1930), directed by Josef von Sternberg (tomorrow and Sunday at 6:30 p.m.)Museum hours: Wednesdays and Thursdays, noon to 5 p.m.; Fridays, noon to 8 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, 11 a.m. to 6:30 p.m.; and by appointment. Film and video showings are free with admission unless otherwise noted. Museum admission: $10; 65+ and students, $7.50; ages 5 to 18, $5; free for members and children 4 and younger and for everyone on Fridays from 4 to 8 p.m.; Friday-night screenings are extra. Information: www.movingimage.us or (718)784-0077.

NEW YORK TRANSIT MUSEUM, Boerum Place and Schermerhorn Street, Brooklyn Heights. Tomorrow at 1 p.m., "Songfest," with classic transportation songs, games and interactive stories led by children's entertainer Jonathan Bayer; free with museum admission. Sunday at noon, "IND Queens Boulevard Line," tour of subway service in Queens. Fee: $20; $15, members. Reservations and meeting place: (718)694-1867. Through the spring, "The City Beneath Us: Building the New York Subway," an exhibition of photographs taken during the construction of the system between 1900 and 1928. Tuesdays through Fridays, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., and Saturdays and Sundays, noon to 5 p.m. Admission: $5; children 3 to 17, $3; members, 62+ and children under 3, free. Information: (718)694-1600.